If you're referring to the BAGEL4 bioinformatics tool for mining RiPPs and bacteriocins, there is no official Conda/Bioconda package for BAGEL4. The developers distribute it as a standalone Perl application with several external dependencies. 

1. Create a Conda environment

You can still use Conda to manage most dependencies:

conda create -n bagel4 \
    perl \
    hmmer \
    blast \
    glimmerhmm \
    python=3.10 \
    -c conda-forge -c bioconda

conda activate bagel4

Some BAGEL4 dependencies (such as PfamScan and its databases) may require manual installation. 

2. Download BAGEL4

git clone https://github.com/annejong/BAGEL4.git
cd BAGEL4

or download the release archive from the repository. 

3. Configure BAGEL4

Edit:

nano bagel4.conf

Update paths to:

HMMER (hmmsearch)

BLAST

Glimmer

Pfam databases

Output directories


The README notes that bagel4.conf must be adapted to your system before running. 

4. Set the Perl library path

BAGEL4 ships with Perl modules in its lib directory:

export PERL5LIB=$(pwd)/lib:$PERL5LIB

The project documentation specifically requires adding the BAGEL4 library to PERL5LIB. 

5. Install databases

BAGEL4 requires:

Pfam-A HMM database

Pfam FASTA database

Optional UniRef database


After downloading Pfam:

gunzip Pfam*.gz
hmmpress Pfam-A.hmm
makeblastdb -in Pfam-A.fasta -dbtype prot

(or formatdb on older BLAST installations). 

6. Run BAGEL4

For a directory of FASTA genomes:

perl bagel4_wrapper.pl \
    -s my_session \
    -i genomes/

Common options include:

-s   session/output directory
-i   input FASTA folder or zip file
-r   filename regex

The wrapper recursively processes FASTA files and creates a results session directory. 

Example

conda activate bagel4

export PERL5LIB=/path/to/BAGEL4/lib:$PERL5LIB

cd /path/to/BAGEL4

perl bagel4_wrapper.pl \
    -s results \
    -i genomes/

Troubleshooting

"Can't locate module" → PERL5LIB is not set correctly.

Pfam errors → download and index the Pfam databases.

MOODS folder errors → create the symbolic link described in the README. Several users have reported setup issues related to missing MOODS files. 

Large projects (>40 genomes) → the BAGEL4 developers recommend using the standalone Linux version rather than the public web server. 


